2131,IssuesEvent,2016-06-21 18:08:15+00:00,52703965,moses-palmer/pystray,10568289,lancekindle,,,opened,This platform is not supported,[],[],0,"I directly imported pystray after installing with pip3
> ImportError: this platform is not supported

I'm currently on ubuntu.
Doing a little digging, I went through the imports one by one and found Xlib is not installed.

`pip3 install python3-xlib`

ah... I think I see how this is a problem.
Since python-xlib does not install on python3,
and python3-xlib does not installl on python2,
trying to create a universal pystray will fail since you can't require the same type of packages.

I think getting a more informative error (in case an import fails) would be useful.
",{},{}
2136,IssuesEvent,2017-11-18 14:15:39+00:00,6054289,niklasf/python-chess,402777,niklasf,,,closed,LegalMoveGenerator can run generate_legal_moves() twice when creating a list,[],[],2,"Python-chess is great!

But I have found that

`list(board.legal_moves)`

or

`[*board.legal_moves]`

to get a list is unnecessarily slow because generate_legal_moves() is called twice. (First from `__len__` of the LegalMoveGenerator, and then from `__iter__`.)

`[x for x in board.legal_moves]`

on the other hand is much faster because this double calling does not happen.

It took me quite a bit of profiling with SnakeViz and stack traces to figure this out, so maybe LegalMoveGenerator should get a to_list() method that returns a list in the fastest way possible.
",{},{}
