4004,IssuesEvent,2018-02-03 22:31:42+00:00,5888353,spotify/luigi,1796164,andyalky,251374,spotify,opened,luigi.contrib.sqla - Boolean values now cause a type error,[],[],0,"I have a script that, as part of my data pipeline, loads a TSV file to a database. This is done through the luigi.contrib.sqla module.

SQLAlchemy released version 1.2 on January 24th. When I upgraded SQLAlchemy from version 1.1 to version 1.2, I started getting the following errors when running my script:

```
File ""[...]/env/lib/python3.6/site-packages/sqlalchemy/sql/sqltypes.py"", line 1653, in _strict_as_bool
    ""Not a boolean value: %r"" % value)
TypeError: Not a boolean value: 'True'
```

My database contains Boolean values, and previously, all my Boolean values were represented as ""True"" or ""False"" in my TSV input files. I tried changing the values in the TSV to ""0"" and ""1"", yet the error persisted. 

I checked SQLAlchemy's release notes, and the new release mandated that Boolean values no longer be passed through as strings.

According to their documentation:

> ""The ultimate solution to this problem is that **string values are not supported with Boolean**, so in 1.2 a hard TypeError is raised if a non-integer / True/False/None value is passed. Additionally, only the integer values 0 and 1 are accepted.""
(http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/latest/changelog/migration_12.html#boolean-datatype-now-enforces-strict-true-false-none-values)

When I downgrade my SQLAlchemy to 1.1, my script works as intended.

SQLAlchemy's release notes propose a fix by using SQLAlchemy's TypeDecorator. I'd like to try implementing this, but I'm not sure if there is a better/easier way to fix this issue for Luigi.

Would I be correct in suspecting that, due to SQLAlchemy's recent release, luigi.contrib.sqla is no longer able to handle Boolean values as expected?

Thanks!",{},{}
4005,IssuesEvent,2016-12-07 10:39:29+00:00,5888353,spotify/luigi,294349,Tarrasch,251374,spotify,closed,task_namespace lost during inheritance,[],[],1,"Hey guys!

When inheriting from a task class that has a `task_namespace`, imho it would be pythonic that the inheriting class has the same `task_namespace` (if not set otherwise). However, this does not seem to be the case. Is this behavior intended by design?

### Possible solution

Due to the way the task register meta class implements the `_default_namespace` fallback, the proper namespace is only set when it's contained in the `class_dict`: ([link](https://github.com/spotify/luigi/blob/master/luigi/task_register.py#L67))

```python
class Register(abc.ABCMeta):

    def __new__(metacls, classname, bases, classdict):
        if ""task_namespace"" not in classdict:
            classdict[""task_namespace""] = metacls._default_namespace

        cls = super(Register, metacls).__new__(metacls, classname, bases, classdict)
        metacls._reg.append(cls)
```

The fix would be quite simple:

```python
class Register(abc.ABCMeta):

    def __new__(metacls, classname, bases, classdict):
        cls = super(Register, metacls).__new__(metacls, classname, bases, classdict)

        if not getattr(cls, ""task_namespace"", None):
            cls.task_namespace = metacls._default_namespace

        metacls._reg.append(cls)
```

This implies a minor change though: the inherited namespace would be favored over the default one, except when the inherited one is falsy.

Any thoughts?",{},{}
