5457,IssuesEvent,2017-06-09 16:30:12+00:00,81612762,trailofbits/manticore,2467355,mossberg,2314423,trailofbits,opened,Implement virtual filesystem,"[{'id': 598241611, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/trailofbits/manticore/labels/idea', 'name': 'idea', 'color': '0052cc', 'default': False}]",[],0,"Currently, if a program does filesystem operations, Manticore's os model will simply forward those to  the host OS (e.g. a program calls `chdir`, Manticore chdirs itself to the destination directory).

This is not ideal because we want analysis to be as contained as possible to the virtual execution environment Manticore creates. Honoring these system calls directly creates potential for a malicious program to potentially affect the host analysis system in an undesirable way.

Relevant: #295 ",{},{}
5474,IssuesEvent,2016-11-22 18:56:27+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,464308,yoavg,2374376,clab,opened,non-standard dropout behavior,"[{'id': 439661365, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/clab/dynet/labels/moderate%20bug', 'name': 'moderate bug', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False}]",[],0,"The `dropout` node implementation is non-standard: it drops nodes with prob (1-p) but also multiplies the remaining nodes by 1/(1-p) to compensate. This is indeed very convenient as you don't have to do anything special at test time (other than not applying dropout), but I'd imagine 99% of the users (those who don't wrote the function or looked closely at its code) don't know this, and will apply their own additional scaling at test time, hurting their results. I know I was bitten by this.

The least we could do is add this to the documentation, but I suspect most users will still miss this (as they assume they already know what dropout does and won't read). So I am in favor of changing the dropout node such that the internal-scaling behavior is controlled by a parameter that is *off* by default (i.e., make it opt-in, not opt-out).

Or we could have a VERY visible doc page on ""Unorthodox things"", and make sure to document it there.
",{},{}
