6093,IssuesEvent,2018-07-31 00:47:40+00:00,10866320,pyamg/pyamg,1615863,lukeolson,4763879,pyamg,closed,Some potentially interesting benchmarks,[],[],19,"Just ran into pyamg; great to see these complex algorithms be made available in such a neat package!

I started to try out pyamg in some of the more complex solves in my project, and these gave the following results; which perhaps could be improved upon by those with more knowhow of amg; and would perhaps be interesting additions to the examples/benchmarks.

The first thing I tried was a darcy-flow with high anisotropy; like groundwater that is free to move in some cracks but not in other places. [runnable example here](https://github.com/EelcoHoogendoorn/pycomplex/blob/master/examples/flow/darcy_flow.py). Even for modest grid sizes this solve takes several tens of seconds. This strikes me as the killer-app of amg; where it has the potential to even blow geometric multigrid out of the water.. But I havnt been able to realize anything but modest gains so far; about 20% over a minres solve. That strikes me as way below expectations. Maybe it is because I am trying to solve it as a mixed pressure-velocity formulation, and this complicates aggregation? (update; the difference is more like 40% on my 2-core last gen i5; as opposed to the 20% on my ancient 4-core i7. this leaves amg only 3-4 times slower on the highly anisotropic case compared to solving the same problem with purely isotropic coefficients. That isnt too bad; I suppose? Or could we do better with the right choice of parameters?)

The other thing I tried is more or less an exact copy-paste from the poisson eigenmodes example. [runnable example here](https://github.com/EelcoHoogendoorn/pycomplex/blob/master/examples/harmonics/spherical.py)
Here I am getting some decent gains for highly refined grids; but for refinement=6 grids and K=200 I get this error.

`numpy.linalg.linalg.LinAlgError: the leading minor of order 376 of 'b' is not positive definite. The factorization of 'b' could not be completed and no eigenvalues or eigenvectors were computed.
`

Note that there are perfectly well formed laplacian operators; L * D * L.T, with L full rank and D a positive diagonal). Seems like a numerical stability issue; Any ideas for how to mitigate/solve this?",{},{}
