6341,IssuesEvent,2016-04-27 08:54:53+00:00,3920766,manahl/mockextras,90507,darkip,5859004,manahl,closed,unhelpful KeyError raised when mismatch on calls,[],[],2,"```
from unittest import TestCase

from mock import Mock, call
from mockextras import stub


class Appender:

    def __init__(self):
        self.appended = []

    def append(self, message):
        self.appended.append(message)
        return True

class AppenderTest(TestCase):

    def test_this_one_works(self):

        foo = Mock()
        appended = ""a""
        foo.append.side_effect = stub((call(appended), True))
        foo.append(""a"")
        self.assertEquals(foo.mock_calls, [call.append(appended)])

    def test_this_one_barfs_with_KeyError_but_should_really_be_more_helpful(self):

        foo = Mock()
        appended = ""a a""
        foo.append.side_effect = stub((call(appended), True))
        foo.append(""a"")
        self.assertEquals(foo.mock_calls, [call.append(appended)])
```

Help could be calls that were close but not exact. In this case the intended and actual call were (re a string param) different by a couple of chars. It'd be a huge help for a string diff to be shown.  Sure that's if the param in question is diffable. Even if not, there's a kinder way of raising an error:

```
append(""a"") called, yet there were no stubs to match that. Instead, these were available for matching:
append(""a a"")
```
",{},{}
6350,IssuesEvent,2016-03-20 08:39:48+00:00,41284151,frictionlessdata/tabulator-py,791678,pwalsh,5912125,frictionlessdata,opened,Encoding and recoding,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/frictionlessdata/tabulator-py/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],0,"See https://github.com/openspending/openspending/issues/897

We need the ability to recode a file to utf-8, creating this file as a side effect of a recode processor.

Internally, Tabulator is recoding as utf-8 anyway, as goodtables is. 

I'm not sure exactly the steps required: maybe there are alternatives to having a dedicated processor to produce the output file, but at a high-level view it seems reasonable.",{},{}
