deis-logger.service: loaded
deis-logspout.service: loaded
Control plane...
deis-builder.service: loaded
deis-registry@1.service: loaded
deis-controller.service: loaded
deis-database.service: loaded
Data plane...
deis-publisher.service: loaded
Router mesh...
deis-router@3.service: loaded
deis-router@1.service: loaded
deis-router@2.service: loaded
Done.

Please run `deisctl start platform` to boot up Deis.
● ▴ ■
■ ● ▴ Starting Deis...
▴ ■ ●
Storage subsystem...                 
deis-store-monitor.service: activating/start-pre                     
deis-store-monitor.service: active/running                           
INFO client.go:297: Response 500 Internal Server Error from http://127.0.0.1:4001/ unusable
ERROR client.go:213: Unable to get result for {Set /_coreos.com/fleet/job/deis-store-daemon.service/target-state}, retrying in 100ms

Deis failed to start deis-store-monitor properly.
<exit nonzero>
```

### Why?
I find the first (current) output and process of a `deis start platform` to be confusing. There are a lot of interspersed errors from fleetctl, deisctl... and for a new user there would be lots of confusion as to... hey this didn't seem so clean... do I actually trust the output that I have a working cluster? (in many cases the cluster is in a horribly broken state).

I'd like to see `deis start platform` behavior that more adequately reports the status of the cluster. Ideally we should also be checking the health of etcd and fleet as we go through the start process.

Benefits of this change would be:
- fail fast install/start behavior that would be greatly appreciated by Jenkins so that we didn't continue on our merry way trying to run tests on flaky clusters.
- a more solid ""the install worked or it didn't"" response",{},{}
