6537,IssuesEvent,2017-10-07 15:28:21+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,11278668,bwohlberg,6392739,conda,opened,Installation of python 3.3 and 3.4 fail due to pysocks dependency,[],[],0,"Recent changes (this was working a few days ago) appear to have broken python 3.3 and 3.4:

```
$ wget https://repo.continuum.io/miniconda/Miniconda3-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh -O miniconda.sh
$ bash miniconda.sh -b -p $HOME/miniconda
$ export PATH=""$HOME/miniconda/bin:$PATH""
$ conda update --yes -q conda
$ conda install --yes python=3.4
Fetching package metadata ...........
Solving package specifications: .

UnsatisfiableError: The following specifications were found to be in conflict:
  - pysocks -> python 3.6*
  - python 3.4*
```

Doing `conda info pysocks` indicates that there are no versions of the package available for python 3.3 and 3.4. It's not clear whether this issue is due to removal of these packages, or the introduction of a spurious dependency.",{},{}
6538,IssuesEvent,2015-04-13 19:45:31+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,4328,tswicegood,6392739,conda,closed,Feature discussion: environment hierarchy,[],[],4,"I like to use separate environments for my various projects, and various *branches* of various projects. However, I also like to keep my environments updated (except for the odd testing against older dependency versions). Currently, if e.g. scikit-image gets a new version, I have to go into each environment and `conda update scikit-image`. It would be cool if I could define environments hierarchically. Example:

- I have my py3 root env (python==3.4 + anaconda),
- then I clone that to projA (python==3.4 + anaconda + projA-master + projA-requirements.txt),
- then I clone that environment to projA-branch1 (python==3.4 + anaconda + projA-branch1 + projA-branch1-requirements.txt)

when I update scikit-image in the root, that update gets propagated down the hierarchy. (but the other direction doesn't.)

This is something I've wished for quite a few times but might be difficult / rife with problems / undesirable for some reason I haven't considered. Have the conda devs considered this design and if so is there any chance of it being implemented?

Feel free to just close this if it doesn't make sense — I'd just like to know what you guys think of it.

Thanks!",{},{}
6542,IssuesEvent,2016-06-29 15:35:36+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1042804,mingwandroid,6392739,conda,opened,conda activate and deactivate need to add and remove entries from PATH.,[],[],0,"Reference: https://github.com/matplotlib/matplotlib/pull/6520

When an environment is first activated, `CONDA_PATH_BACKUP` is set to the current value of `PATH`, and when it is deactivated `PATH` is restored to that value.

Unfortunately, this means that modifications to `PATH` between these times are lost. Worse, in particular the `PATH` modifications done by `vcvars.bat` are lost.

I propose a slight modification to how this is being handled. Instead we need to add and remove entries during `activate` and `deactivate` respectively. A `deactivate` followed by an immediate `activate` needs special handling so that it inserts the `conda` paths at the *same place*, perhaps by being told that this is happening and inserting a special token we can replace later (here I've called it `CONDA_PATHS_HERE`).

```
PATH=C:\msysGit\bin;C:\somefolder;C:\miniconda\bin;C:\miniconda\Library\bin;C:\someotherfolder
$ deactivate(newenv=_build) =>
PATH=C:\msysGit\bin;C:\somefolder;CONDA_PATHS_HERE;C:\someotherfolder
$ deactivate(newenv=None) =>
PATH=C:\msysGit\bin;C:\somepath;C:\someotherpath
$ activate(env=_build,PATH=C:\msysGit\bin;C:\somepath;CONDA_PATHS_HERE;C:\someotherpath) =>
PATH=C:\msysGit\bin;C:\somepath;C:\miniconda\envs\_build\bin;C:\miniconda\envs\_build\Library\bin;C:\someotherpath
$ activate(env=_build,PATH=C:\msysGit\bin;C:\somepath;C:\someotherpath) =>
PATH=C:\miniconda\envs\_build\bin;C:\miniconda\envs\_build\Library\bin;C:\msysGit\bin;C:\somepath;C:\someotherpath
```
",{},{}
