7488,IssuesEvent,2016-11-07 15:37:23+00:00,533328,pyelasticsearch/pyelasticsearch,295816,erikrose,10234413,pyelasticsearch,closed,No way to sort queries from Elasticsearch,[],[],1,"looking at the docs https://pyelasticsearch.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/#pyelasticsearch.ElasticSearch.search and source. There's no way to specify how to tell Elasticsearch to sort results.

For example, a full query body might be:
```
{
  ""query"": { ""match_all"": {} },
  ""sort"": [
    { ""account_number"": ""asc"" }
  ]
}
```
You can get `query` in, but not `sort`.",{},{}
7504,IssuesEvent,2017-10-23 23:17:24+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,2379650,sloria,10334301,marshmallow-code,closed,validate.URL rejects hostnames with no dots,[],[],0,"My current use case:
I use Docker and I need to set some URL fields for the containers to communicate together. The URL fields look like `http://third-party/test`, where `third-party` is the hostname of one of the containers.

Currently, `validate.URL` rejects this URL as invalid, because there is no dot in the hostname `third-party`.

Other use cases include:
* a local network in the same subdomain, where hosts are queried using only the name of the machine, not the FQDN, having configured the DNS resolver to search `example.com` automatically, for example `webclient.example.com` querying `webserver` instead of `webserver.example.com`
* a stricly-local network, where there are no public TLD available, and all machines are name `machine1`, `machine2`, etc. very similarly to the Docker internal network",{},{}
7513,IssuesEvent,2015-04-12 21:18:42+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,2379650,sloria,10334301,marshmallow-code,closed,UnmarshallingError with None value in DateTime field,[],[],1,"When your schema contains `DateTime` field (even if `required=False`) and you trying to update this field (with `PATCH` method, for example) `UnmarshalResult` exception will be raised.

I think same result will be with all date\time fileds: `DateTime`, `LocalDateTime`, `Time`, `Date`, 

**Example:**
```Python
from marshmallow import fields, Schema


class TestSchema(Schema):
    string_field = fields.String()
    datetime_field = fields.DateTime()


schema = TestSchema()
schema.load({'datetime_field': None})
```
Result of this code will be `UnmarshalResult`:
```
UnmarshalResult(data={'datetime_field': None}, errors={'datetime_field': [u'Could not deserialize None to a datetime object.']})
```

**Workaround:**
You can extend `DateTime` field like this:
```Python
from marshmallow import fields


class DateTime(fields.DateTime):
    """"""Same as the DateTime from marshmallow.fields,
    but allows datetime to be None
    """"""

    def _deserialize(self, value):
        if not self.required and value is None:
            return value

        return super(DateTime, self)._deserialize(value)
```

**Code:**
Problem in `_deserialize` method of `DateTime`, `Time` and `Date` classes. [Example](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/blob/1.2.4/marshmallow/fields.py#L955) from `DateTime`:
```Python
        msg = 'Could not deserialize {0!r} to a datetime object.'.format(value)
        err = UnmarshallingError(getattr(self, 'error', None) or msg)
        if not value:  # Falsy values, e.g. '', None, [] are not valid
            raise err
```
Other fields have similar checks.

**Version:** 1.2.4",{},{}
7517,IssuesEvent,2018-07-10 18:09:48+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,3083011,yaheath,10334301,marshmallow-code,closed,recent commit breaks use of exclude with marshmallow-sqlalchemy,[],[],3,"Commit 76e8c91e3decfa4f01ee3c48d71995d2e0a55a27 breaks our use of `exclude` in the Meta of a sqlalchemy-backed model schema.

For example:

```python
class CustomerSchema(BaseSchema):
    class Meta(BaseSchema.Meta):
        model = Customer
        exclude = ('orders',)
```

Where `Customer` is a sqlalchemy model and `orders` is a relation from another table. Putting the exclude in the Meta prevents marshmallow-sqlalchemy from creating the Relation field for `orders` into CustomerSchema. However, with the above commit which adds a check on the excludes, it'll now throw an exception at instantiation because 'orders' doesn't exist in the schema (because it was excluded!)

How should this be resolved? I could instead use `fields=()` in the Meta and explicitly list out the fields I want instead of using `exclude`, but that's more maintenance overhead (we have to remember to update the fields list if a column is added to the model)",{},{}
