8991,IssuesEvent,2018-08-15 03:07:38+00:00,71932349,ray-project/ray,38442610,luochao1024,22125274,ray-project,opened,Are the default configs in a3c set specifically for pong?,[],[],0,"<!--
General questions should be asked on the mailing list ray-dev@googlegroups.com.

Before submitting an issue, please fill out the following form.
-->

### System information
- **OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04)**: 16.04
- **Ray installed from (source or binary)**: source
- **Ray version**: 0.5.0
- **Python version**: 3.5.1
- **Exact command to reproduce**: 

<!--
You can obtain the Ray version with

python -c ""import ray; print(ray.__version__)""
-->

### Describe the problem
<!-- Describe the problem clearly here. --> 
I try to run A3C on different atari environments including BreakoutDeterministic-v4, SpaceInvadersDeterministic-v4, QbertDeterministic-v4. The command I use is

` python/ray/rllib/train.py --env=BreakoutDeterministic-v4 --run=A3C --config='{""num_workers"": 16}'.
`

It seems like this command only works for Pong. When it comes to other atari games, it does not work.


After 2 hours running, the `episode_reward_mean `for Breakout can not exceed 10 and the `episode_reward_mean `for Qbert can not exceed 500. As for SpaceInvaders, the `episode_reward_mean `is always between 100 and 300. 

Does anyone successfully run A3C on any other environment except Pong ? Can you share the configs with me? 


### Source code / logs
<!-- Include any logs or source code that would be helpful to diagnose the problem. If including tracebacks, please include the full traceback. Large logs and files should be attached. Try to provide a reproducible test case that is the bare minimum necessary to generate the problem. -->
",{},{}
9003,IssuesEvent,2017-05-07 04:17:50+00:00,71932349,ray-project/ray,249517,robertnishihara,22125274,ray-project,closed,Jenkins tests hanging on remove_driver_test.py.,"[{'id': 468774484, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ray-project/ray/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ee0701', 'default': True}]",[],1,"When running `remove_driver_test.py`, which can be done by first doing `./build-docker.sh` and then running

```
python test/jenkins_tests/multi_node_docker_test.py \
    --num-nodes=5 \
    --num-gpus=0,1,2,3,4 \
    --num-drivers=7 \
    --driver-locations=0,1,0,1,2,3,4 \
    --test-script=/ray/test/jenkins_tests/multi_node_tests/remove_driver_test.py
```

the test often hangs. In particular the driver with `driver_index == 2` hangs. This seems to happen because it is hanging while waiting for a broadcast message from one of the long-running tasks started by either driver 0 or 1. However, one of those drivers prints an error message saying that it was asked to execute the task but it never imported the relevant remote function.

The underlying problem seems to be that multiple drivers are exporting remote functions with the same function ID. This means that the function information is stored at the same key in Redis and they are overriding each other. This can be fixed by simply making the keys globally unique (e.g., appending a random string).",{},{}
9004,IssuesEvent,2017-08-29 16:57:11+00:00,71932349,ray-project/ray,431588,dcrankshaw,22125274,ray-project,opened,Renamed function in ProximalLossPolicy breaks PolicyGradient,[],[],0,"#849 renamed the function in [this line](https://github.com/ray-project/ray/blob/e1831792f846dd0869b472e8b932f6b677ed0ca2/python/ray/rllib/policy_gradient/loss.py#L85) from `compute_actions` to `compute`.

When the function is [called from policy_gradient.py](https://github.com/ray-project/ray/blob/e1831792f846dd0869b472e8b932f6b677ed0ca2/python/ray/rllib/policy_gradient/policy_gradient.py#L270) the function is now called with the wrong name and it causes an error.

I fixed it by just changing the function name back to `compute_actions` which works for my use case, but I didn't look into whether anything else calls the function with the new name.

Relevant stacktrace:
```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""pong_model_container.py"", line 33, in <module>
    test()
  File ""pong_model_container.py"", line 30, in test
